{"title_page": "Mark Pendergrast", "text_new": "{{for|the similarly named Scottish actor|Mark Prendergast}}\n{{Lead too short|date=April 2010}}\n\n'''Mark Pendergrast''' (born 1948) is an [[United States|American]] [[independent scholar]] and author of fourteen books, including three children's books. \n\n==Biography==\nPendergrast was born in 1948 to Nan and Britt Pendergrast,<ref>[[Mirror Mirror: a history of the human love affair with reflection|Mirror Mirror]], dedication on flyleaf</ref> the fourth of seven children. He was raised in [[Atlanta, Georgia]]. He earned a Bachelor of Arts degree in [[English Literature]] from [[Harvard College]], after which he taught for several years in public schools. Pendergrast later attended [[Simmons College in Boston]], where he obtained a Master of Arts degree in [[Library Science]]. He worked as an academic librarian and freelance writer until becoming a full-time writer in 1991. Pendergrast lives in [[Colchester, Vermont]].<ref>[https://www.nasw.org/find-writer?field_last_name_value=pendergrast&field_specialties_value=All&field_expertise_value=All&combine=&combine_1=&field_home_address_country=US Science Writers Index]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nPendergrast has published fourteen books on various topics. Two are histories of caffeinated beverages: Coca-Cola (''For God, Country and Coca-Cola'') and coffee (''Uncommon Grounds''). He has written about a wide array of subjects, such as human memory and its malleability (''Memory Warp''; ''The Repressed Memory Epidemic''; ''Victims of Memory''), a history of mirrors (''Mirror Mirror''); a book about epidemiology and public health (''Inside the Outbreaks''); a book on the Jerry Sandusky case involving repressed memories (''The Most Hated Man in America''); a book about his birth city of Atlanta (''City on the Verge''), a book about Japan and its renewable energy policies after Fukushima (''Japan\u2019s Tipping Point''); a book about a [[Hill tribe (Thailand)|hill tribe]] in Thailand that grows coffee rather than opium poppies (''Beyond Fair Trade''). Several of his books have been translated into multiple languages.\n\nHis three children's books are ''Jack and the Bean Soup''; ''Silly Sadie''; and ''The Godfool''. He has also appeared in several documentaries, including ''[[Black Coffee (2007 film)|Black Coffee]]'' and ''Cola Conquest'', which were in part inspired by his books. Pendergrast also helped to edit and publish ''The Aftermath: A Survivor\u2019s Odyssey Through War-Torn Europe'', a Holocaust memoir by Henry Lilienheim, ''Shift'', poems by Marylen Grigas; ''Neighborhood Naturalist'', by Nan Pendergrast; and ''For Love of the British Isles'', by Nan Pendergrast.\n\nPendergrast has also reviewed books for ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' and ''[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]''. He has contributed articles to the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'', the ''[[New York Times]]'', the ''[[Financial Analyst]]'', ''[[The Baltimore Sun|The Sun]]'', ''[[Vermont Life Magazine]]'', ''[[Burlington Free Press]]'', Vanguard, ''[[Sea History (magazine)|Sea History]]'', ''[[Library Journal]]'', ''[[Atlanta Magazine]]'', ''Vermont Digger'', ''Saporta Report'', ''Fresh Cup, Tea & Coffee Trade Journal'', ''Business People'', ''[[Professional Psychology]]'', ''[[Wine Spectator]]'', and other publications.\n\nHe has spoken at scientific and journalism seminars, book festivals, public events, and on college campuses and has appeared on various television\nand radio programs, including ''[[The Today Show]]'', ''[[All Things Considered]]'', ''[[Marketplace (Canadian TV program)|Marketplace]]'', and ''[[Fresh Air]]''. He writes a semi-regular column about coffee for the ''[[Wine Spectator]]''.\n\nPendergrast is a member of the [[National Association of Science Writers]], the [[Society of Environmental Journalists]], the League of Vermont Writers, and the [[Authors Guild]]. He is a volunteer for the [[National Center for Reason and Justice]], a [[nonprofit organization]] which works with innocent people [[falsely accused]] or convicted of [[child abuse]] (related to the subject of his book ''Memory Warp'').\n\n== Published works ==\n===Jerry Sandusky===\nJoseph Stains reviews Pendergrast's 2017 book ''The Most Hated Man in America: Jerry Sandusky and the Rush to Judgement''. Stain says it is \"probably the most evenhanded and thoroughly documented volume on the topic\". Pendergrast detailed the trial and did extensive research on the subject of [[Jerry Sandusky]]'s 2012 guilty verdict for sexual abuse of young men at [[Penn State]]. Stains writes that Pendergrast made a compelling case that the small-town lawyer Sandusky chose to represent him and a prosecution that relied on [[repressed memory|repressed memories]], no physical evidence and possible financial motives may have been the factors that led to the court finding him guilty. Stains states that Pendergrast \"has done meticulous background work... and he provides material background for answering any question one may pose to him\".<ref name=\"Stains\">{{cite journal|last1=Joseph|first1=Stains|title=Reconsidering Monsters|journal=Skeptical Inquirer|date=2018|volume=42|issue=3|pages=62\u201363|publisher=Committee for Skeptical Inquiry}}</ref>\n\n=== Non-fiction ===\n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=Victims of Memory: Sex Abuse Accusations and Shattered Lives|publisher=Upper Access|year=1996| edition=2nd|isbn=0-942679-18-0}} \n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=[[Mirror Mirror: A History of the Human Love Affair With Reflection]]|year=2003|isbn=0-465-05470-6|publisher=[[Basic Books]]}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=Uncommon Grounds: The History of Coffee and How It Transformed Our World|publisher=[[Basic Books]]|year=2010|edition=2nd|isbn=0-465-05467-6}} \n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=Inside the Outbreaks: The Elite Medical Detectives of the Epidemic Intelligence Service|publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]]|year=2010|isbn=978-0-15-101120-9}} \n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=Japan's Tipping Point: Crucial Choices in the Post-Fukushima World|publisher=Nature's Face Publications|year=2011|isbn=978-0982900437}} \n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=For God, Country, and Coca-Cola: The Definitive History of the Great American Soft Drink and the Company That Makes It|publisher=[[Basic Books]]|year=2013 |edition=3rd|isbn=0-465-05468-4}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=Beyond Fair Trade: How One Small Coffee Company Helped Transform a Hillside Village in Thailand|publisher=[[Greystone Books]]|year=2015|isbn=978-1771640473}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=City on the Verge: Atlanta and the Fight for America\u2019s Urban Future|publisher=[[Basic Books]]|year=2017|isbn=978-0465054732}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=Memory Warp: How the Myth of Repressed Memories Arose and Refuses to Die|publisher=Upper Access|year=2017|isbn=978-0-942679-41-0}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=The Repressed Memory Epidemic: How It Happened and What We Need to Learn from It.|publisher=[[Springer Publishing|Springer]]|year=2017|isbn=978-3319633749}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=The Most Hated Man in America: Jerry Sandusky and the Rush to Judgement|publisher=[[Sunbury Press|Sunbury]]|year=2017|isbn=978-1620067659}}\n\n=== Children's literature ===\n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=Jack and the Bean Soup|year=2010|publisher=Nature's Face Publications|isbn=978-0982900406}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=Silly Sadie|year=2013|publisher=Nature's Face Publications|isbn=978-0982900451}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=The Godfool|year=2015|publisher=Nature's Face Publications|isbn=978-0982900475}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.markpendergrast.com}}\n* {{OL author}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Mark Pendergrast}}\n**{{cite web|title=Interview on CSPAN|url=http://www.booknotes.org/Watch/151209-1/Mark-Pendergrast.aspx|website=www.booknotes.org|accessdate=March 7, 2018|date=August 29, 1999}}\n**{{cite web|title=City on the Verge: Atlanta and the Fight for America\u2019s Urban Future|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?428815-1/city-verge|date=May 25, 2017}}\n**{{cite web|title=For God, Country, and Coca-Cola: The Definitive History of the Great American Soft Drink and the Company That Makes It|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?314405-1/for-god-country-coca-cola|date=July 24, 2013}}\n**{{cite web|title=Inside the Outbreaks: The Elite Medical Detectives of the Epidemic Intelligence Service|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?297317-1/inside-outbreaks |date=Sep 25, 2010}}\n**{{cite web|title=Uncommon Grounds: The History of Coffee and How it Transformed Our World|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?155156-1/uncommon-grounds|date=Jan 29, 2000}}\n*[https://rose.library.emory.edu/ Stuart A. Rose Manuscript, Archives, and Rare Book Library], Emory University: [http://pid.emory.edu/ark:/25593/8zrn3 Mark Pendergrast research files, circa 1880-2009]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pendergrast, Mark}}\n[[Category:American science writers]]\n[[Category:American librarians]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Independent scholars]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the similarly named Scottish actor|Mark Prendergast}}\n{{Lead too short|date=April 2010}}\n\n'''Mark Pendergrast''' (born 1948) is an [[United States|American]] [[independent scholar]] and author of fourteen books, including three children's books. \n\n==Biography==\nPendergrast was born in 1948 to Nan and Britt Pendergrast,<ref>[[Mirror Mirror: a history of the human love affair with reflection|Mirror Mirror]], dedication on flyleaf</ref> the fourth of seven children. He was raised in [[Atlanta, Georgia]]. He earned a Bachelor of Arts degree in [[English Literature]] from [[Harvard College]], after which he taught for several years in public schools. Pendergrast later attended [[Simmons College in Boston]], where he obtained a Master of Arts degree in [[Library Science]]. He worked as an academic librarian and freelance writer until becoming a full-time writer in 1991. Pendergrast lives in [[Colchester, Vermont]].<ref>[https://www.nasw.org/find-writer?field_last_name_value=pendergrast&field_specialties_value=All&field_expertise_value=All&combine=&combine_1=&field_home_address_country=US Science Writers Index]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nPendergrast has published fourteen books on various topics. Two are histories of caffeinated beverages: Coca-Cola (''For God, Country and Coca-Cola'') and coffee (''Uncommon Grounds''). He has written about a wide array of subjects, such as human memory and its malleability (''Memory Warp''; ''The Repressed Memory Epidemic''; ''Victims of Memory''), a history of mirrors (''Mirror Mirror''); a book about epidemiology and public health (''Inside the Outbreaks''); a book on the Jerry Sandusky case involving repressed memories (''The Most Hated Man in America''); a book about his birth city of Atlanta (''City on the Verge''), a book about Japan and its renewable energy policies after Fukushima (''Japan\u2019s Tipping Point''); a book about a [[Hill tribe (Thailand)|hill tribe]] in Thailand that grows coffee rather than opium poppies (''Beyond Fair Trade''). Several of his books have been translated into multiple languages.\n\nHis three children's books are ''Jack and the Bean Soup''; ''Silly Sadie''; and ''The Godfool''. He has also appeared in several documentaries, including ''[[Black Coffee (2007 film)|Black Coffee]]'' and ''Cola Conquest'', which were in part inspired by his books. Pendergrast also helped to edit and publish ''The Aftermath: A Survivor\u2019s Odyssey Through War-Torn Europe'', a Holocaust memoir by Henry Lilienheim, ''Shift'', poems by Marylen Grigas; ''Neighborhood Naturalist'', by Nan Pendergrast; and ''For Love of the British Isles'', by Nan Pendergrast.\n\nPendergrast has also reviewed books for ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' and ''[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]''. He has contributed articles to the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'', the ''[[New York Times]]'', the ''[[Financial Analyst]]'', ''[[The Baltimore Sun|The Sun]]'', ''[[Vermont Life Magazine]]'', ''[[Burlington Free Press]]'', Vanguard, ''[[Sea History (magazine)|Sea History]]'', ''[[Library Journal]]'', ''[[Atlanta Magazine]]'', ''Vermont Digger'', ''Saporta Report'', ''Fresh Cup, Tea & Coffee Trade Journal'', ''Business People'', ''[[Professional Psychology]]'', ''[[Wine Spectator]]'', and other publications.\n\nHe has spoken at scientific and journalism seminars, book festivals, public events, and on college campuses and has appeared on various television\nand radio programs, including ''[[The Today Show]]'', ''[[All Things Considered]]'', ''[[Marketplace (Canadian TV program)|Marketplace]]'', and ''[[Fresh Air]]''. He writes a semi-regular column about coffee for the ''[[Wine Spectator]]''.\n\nPendergrast is a member of the [[National Association of Science Writers]], the [[Society of Environmental Journalists]], the League of Vermont Writers, and the [[Authors Guild]]. He is a volunteer for the [[National Center for Reason and Justice]], a [[nonprofit organization]] which works with innocent people [[falsely accused]] or convicted of [[child abuse]] (related to the subject of his book ''Memory Warp'').\n\n== Published works ==\n===Jerry Sandusky===\nJoseph Stains reviews Pendergrast's 2017 book ''The Most Hated Man in America: Jerry Sandusky and the Rush to Judgement''. Stain says it is \"probably the most evenhanded and thoroughly documented volume on the topic\". Pendergrast detailed the trial and did extensive research on the subject of [[Jerry Sandusky]]'s 2012 guilty verdict for sexual abuse of young men at [[Penn State]]. Stains writes that Pendergrast made a compelling case that the small-town lawyer Sandusky chose to represent him and a prosecution that relied on [[repressed memory|repressed memories]], no physical evidence and possible financial motives may have been the factors that led to the court finding him guilty. Stains states that Pendergrast \"has done meticulous background work... and he provides material background for answering any question one may pose to him\".<ref name=\"Stains\">{{cite journal|last1=Joseph|first1=Stains|title=Reconsidering Monsters|journal=Skeptical Inquirer|date=2018|volume=42|issue=3|pages=62\u201363|publisher=Committee for Skeptical Inquiry}}</ref>\n\n=== Non-fiction ===\n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=Victims of Memory: Sex Abuse Accusations and Shattered Lives|publisher=Upper Access|year=1996| edition=2nd|isbn=0-942679-18-0}} \n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=[[Mirror Mirror: A History of the Human Love Affair With Reflection]]|year=2003|isbn=0-465-05470-6|publisher=[[Basic Books]]}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=Uncommon Grounds: The History of Coffee and How It Transformed Our World|publisher=[[Basic Books]]|year=2010|edition=2nd|isbn=0-465-05467-6}} \n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=Inside the Outbreaks: The Elite Medical Detectives of the Epidemic Intelligence Service|publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin Harcourt]]|year=2010|isbn=978-0-15-101120-9}} \n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=Japan's Tipping Point: Crucial Choices in the Post-Fukushima World|publisher=Nature's Face Publications|year=2011|isbn=978-0982900437}} \n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=For God, Country, and Coca-Cola: The Definitive History of the Great American Soft Drink and the Company That Makes It|publisher=[[Basic Books]]|year=2013 |edition=3rd|isbn=0-465-05468-4}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pendergrast|first=Mark|title=Beyond Fair Trade: How One Small Coffee Company Helped Transform a Hillside Village in Thailand|publisher=[[Greystone Books]