{"title_page": "Michael T. Weiss", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Michael T. Weiss\n| image = \n| imagesize =\n| caption = Michael T. Weiss (Pale in Lanford Wilson's play ''Burn This'') during 2004-2005 season\n| birth_name = Michael Terry Weiss\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1962|2|2}}\n| birth_place = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| othername =\n| website =\n| spouse =\n| occupation = Actor\n| years_active = 1980\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Michael Terry Weiss''' (born February 2, 1962) is an American actor who is known for his role as Jarod in the television series ''[[The Pretender (TV series)|The Pretender]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nWeiss was born in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]. His father was a steel industry executive and his mother was a homemaker.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/42/Michael-T-Weiss.html|title=Michael T. Weiss Biography (1962-)|website=www.filmreference.com}}</ref> He has a sister, [[Jamie Sue Weiss]], who became a [[make-up artist]] for television and films.  He went to [[Glenbrook North High School]] in [[Northbrook, Illinois]].  He graduated from the [[University of Southern California]].<ref name=\"Kim\">{{cite web |title=Michael T. Weiss pulls weight in \u2018Bones\u2019 |url=https://www.jaehakim.com/entertainment-reviews/tv-reviews/michael-t-weiss-pulls-weight-in-bones/ |website=Jae-Ha Kim |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nWeiss began acting when he was a child, where he appeared in local TV commercials in Chicago.\n\nIn 1980, at the age of 18, he had his first movie role as an extra in the movie ''[[Ordinary People]]''. Shortly after his college graduation, he obtained his first major role as [[Mike Horton (Days of Our Lives)|Mike Horton]] on ''[[Days of Our Lives]]''. Weiss also starred in the [[NBC-TV]] prime time drama ''[[The Pretender (TV series)|The Pretender]]'' for four seasons as the lead character  [[List of The Pretender (TV series) characters#Jarod|Jarod]]. Weiss also had roles in the movie ''[[Jeffrey (1995 film)|Jeffrey]]'', the animated series ''[[The Legend of Tarzan (TV series)|The Legend of Tarzan]]'', and a recurring role on ''[[Crossing Jordan]]''. He voiced \"The Nameless One\", the protagonist of computer game ''[[Planescape: Torment]]''.\n\nIn February 2006, Weiss attended a benefit with his former ''Pretender'' co-stars [[Andrea Parker]] and [[James Denton]] for [[Cure Autism Now]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cureautismnow.org/site/apps/nl/content2.asp?c=bhLOK2PILuF&b=1289185&ct=1996497 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-01-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208003721/http://www.cureautismnow.org/site/apps/nl/content2.asp?c=bhLOK2PILuF&b=1289185&ct=1996497 |archivedate=February 8, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nWeiss joined the cast of ''[[Impressionism (play)|Impressionism]]'', a play by [[Michael Jacobs (producer)|Michael Jacobs]] and directed by [[Jack O'Brien (director)|Jack O'Brien]].<ref>http://www.newyorktheatreguide.com/news/dec08/impressionism03dec08.htm</ref> It opened at the [[Gerald Schoenfeld Theatre]] on March 12, 2009.\n\nWeiss appeared in ''[[A Perfect Future]]'', [[Off-Broadway]] at the [[Cherry Lane Theatre]]. The production was directed by [[Wilson Milam]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/147725-Donna-Bullock-Scott-Drummond-Daniel-Oreskes-Michael-T-Weiss-Explore-A-Perfect-Future-Opening-Feb-17 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-04-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110425180731/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/147725-Donna-Bullock-Scott-Drummond-Daniel-Oreskes-Michael-T-Weiss-Explore-A-Perfect-Future-Opening-Feb-17 |archivedate=April 25, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 1980 || ''[[Ordinary People]]'' || Extra |